       "'<|im_start|>system\\nYou are Qwen, created by Alibaba Cloud. You are a helpful assistant.<|im_end|>\\n<|im_start|>user\\nYou are an expert multilingual translator specializing in English → French.\\n\\n## Task\\nTranslate the source sentence into French. Reference translations from intermediate pivot systems are provided to assist you, but they may contain errors — treat them as imperfect hints, not ground truth.\\n\\n## Source (English)\\n\"We now have 4-month-old mice that are non-diabetic that used to be diabetic,\" he added.\\n\\n## Pivot Reference Translations\\nEach reference has a quality score (0–1, higher = better).\\n- Il a ajouté : \"Nous avons actuellement des souris non diabétiques âgées de 4 mois, qui étaient previously des souris diabétiques.\" (quality: 0.843)\\n- \"Nous avons actuellement des souris âgées de 4 mois sans diabète qui étaient previously diabétiques,\" a ajouté il. (quality: 0.837)\\n- \"Maintenant nous avons des rats de 4 mois qui ne sont pas diabétiques, alors qu\\'ils l\\'étaient previously,\" a-t-il ajouté. (quality: 0.829)\\n\\n## How to use the references\\n1. **Source is authoritative.** If a reference contradicts the source (wrong names, wrong facts, omissions), trust the source.\\n2. **Weight by quality score.** Higher-scored references are more reliable for phrasing and fluency — prefer them, but verify against the source.\\n3. **Resolve conflicts critically.** When references disagree, check the source to decide which is correct — do not average or blend conflicting facts.\\n4. **Named entities and numbers.** Copy proper nouns, names, and numbers directly from the source if references render them inconsistently.\\n5. **Improve, don\\'t just copy.** You may borrow fluent phrasing from references, but your final translation must be factually accurate and naturally idiomatic.\\n\\n## Output constraints\\n- Output ONLY the final French translation.\\n- No notes, no explanations, no alternatives.\\n\\nFrench:<|im_end|>\\n<|im_start|>assistant\\n'"
